did.abstract: Records of Indiana University president. Organized in two series, the collection primarily consists of incoming correspondence during Swain's tenure. Included are several prominent IU professors such as William Lowe Bryan, David Starr Jordan, and Carl H. Eigenmann as well as a number of well-known public figures.
did.langmaterial: Materials are in English unless otherwise indicated.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Collection is open for research. Advance notice required.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Joseph Swain was the ninth president of Indiana University from 1893 to 1902. He was born on June 16, 1857 in Pendleton, Indiana, the son of Woolston and Mary Ann (Thomas) Swain. Swain attended the academy in Pendleton and then entered Indiana University, graduating with a B.L. degree in 1883 and M.S. in 1885. While at the university, Swain attracted the attention of President David Starr Jordan. Jordan hired him as an assistant instructor of mathematics and biology while Swain pursued his master's degree. Swain met Frances M. Morgan while teaching at IU, and they were married on September 22, 1885 in Knightstown, Indiana. The Swains never had any children. He also took a leave of absence for one year to study abroad at the University of Edinburgh in Scotland and worked with renowned astronomer Piazzi Smith. Swain later published a memoir of his work with Smith in a paper entitled, "An Experience with the Astronomer Royal of Scotland." In 1891 he became head of Leland Stanford University's mathematics department and, two years later, returned to his native state and assumed the presidency of Indiana University for nine years. Swain then left to become president of Swarthmore College outside of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. He resigned from the position in 1921 and died on May 23, 1927 after a long illness. He was buried in Friends Cemetery in Pendleton.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Indiana University President's Office records organized into two series, Addresses and reports and Correspondence.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: Swain's correspondence reveals his dedication to recruiting top notch faculty, raising academic standards, and increasing enrollment at Indiana University. He was president of the Indiana State Teacher's Association from 1893-1894 and very active in the Young Men's Christian Association (Y.M.C.A.) at local, state, and national levels. One of his major concerns was high school and college accreditation; he was a member of the National Education Association (N.E.A.). Swain eventually became the president of the N.E.A. from 1913-1914.

Box 1 contains Swain's speeches, reports to the Trustees, and correspondence relating to the presidency. The remaining boxes consist of university reports and the incoming correspondence of the President's office. The correspondence is quite rich and includes many prominent University figures and several noted national figures.

The final two boxes consist of letter press books, which hold the outgoing correspondence of President Swain and other administrators. The books are in very poor condition with the ink disappearing and are scheduled to be scanned in 2013 in an effort to capture the information. The final volume contains a small amount of William Lowe Bryan's correspondence, who served as Swain's successor.

userestrict.head: Usage Restrictions
userestrict.p: Copyrights for records originating with Indiana University administrative units, departments, and other offices are held by the Trustees of Indiana University. For more information, please contact the Indiana University Archives staff.

The Indiana University Archives respects the intellectual property rights of others and does not claim any copyrights for non-university records, materials in the public domain, or materials for which we do not hold a Deed of Gift. Responsibility for the determination of the copyright status of these materials rests with those persons wishing to reuse the materials. Researchers are responsible for securing permission from copyright owners and any other rights holders for any reuse of these materials that extends beyond fair use or other statutory limitations.

Digital reproductions of archival materials from the Indiana University Archives are made available for noncommercial educational and research purposes only. If you are the copyright holder for any of the digitized materials and have questions about its inclusion on our site, please contact the Indiana University Archivist.
